<refentry id="cdn-monitor">
  <refmeta>
    <refentrytitle>cdn-monitor</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
    <refmiscinfo class="manual">Tools</refmiscinfo>
    <refmiscinfo class="source">libcdn</refmiscinfo>
  </refmeta>

  <info>
    <author>
      <personname>
        <firstname>Jesse</firstname>
        <surname>van den Kieboom</surname>
      </personname>
      <personblurb>Developer</personblurb>
    </author>
  </info>

  <refnamediv>
    <refname>cdn-monitor</refname>
    <refpurpose>cdn network monitoring tool</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>

  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>cdn-monitor</command>
      <arg choice="opt" rep="repeat">OPTION</arg>
      <arg choice="plain">-m <replaceable>SELECTOR</replaceable></arg>
      <arg choice="opt" rep="repeat">-m</arg>
      <arg>NETWORK</arg>
    </cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>

  <refsect1>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para><command>cdn-monitor</command> is a tool to run a CDN network and
      monitor a number of states that you can specify. The tool outputs the
      resulting values for each of the monitored state variables (and time) in
      a delimiter seperated format.
    </para>
    <para>
      If the network file is not specified (or if the specified filename is "-"),
      then the network to monitor will be read from standard input. You have
      to provide always at least one monitoring option -m/--monitor.
    </para>
    <refsect2>
      <title>Options</title>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-h</option>, <option>--help</option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              print help and exit
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>

          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-m <replaceable>SELECTOR</replaceable></option>, <option>--monitor <replaceable>SELECTOR</replaceable></option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              specify a selector which selects state variables to monitor. The selector
              supports the full syntax of the selectors of the CDN specification format.
              You can specify this flag multiple times.
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>

          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-i</option>, <option>--include-header</option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              include a header in the output with delimiter separated column names of the variables
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>

          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-d <replaceable>DELIM</replaceable></option>, <option>--delimiter <replaceable>DELIM</replaceable></option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              specify the delimiter to use in the output (defaults to \t)
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>

          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-t <replaceable>RANGE</replaceable></option>, <option>--time <replaceable>RANGE</replaceable></option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              specify the range of time to simulate the network. <replaceable>RANGE</replaceable>
              is a colon separated string of the following format: FROM:STEP:TO. The
              default value is 0:0.01:1
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>

          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-o <replaceable>FILE</replaceable></option>, <option>--output <replaceable>FILE</replaceable></option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              specify the output file to which the output will be written. This defaults
              to standard output.
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>

          <varlistentry>
            <term><option>-s <replaceable>SEED</replaceable></option>, <option>--seed <replaceable>SEED</replaceable></option></term>
            <listitem><para>
              specify the number by which to seed to random number generator. The default
              value for the seed is the current unix time (seconds since epoch)
            </para></listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </refsect2>
  </refsect1>
</refentry>

